-- Table structure for table `wp_layerslider_revisions`

--


CREATE TABLE `wp_layerslider_revisions` (

  `id` int(10) NOT NULL,

  `slider_id` int(10) NOT NULL,

  `author` int(10) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',

  `data` mediumtext COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL,

  `date_c` int(10) NOT NULL

) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci;


-- --------------------------------------------------------


--

-- Table structure for table `wp_links`

--


CREATE TABLE `wp_links` (

  `link_id` bigint(20) UNSIGNED NOT NULL,

  `link_url` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT '',

  `link_name` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT '',

  `link_image` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT '',

  `link_target` varchar(25) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT '',

  `link_description` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT '',

  `link_visible` varchar(20) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT 'Y',

  `link_owner` bigint(20) UNSIGNED NOT NULL DEFAULT '1',

  `link_rating` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0',

  `link_updated` datetime NOT NULL DEFAULT '0000-00-00 00:00:00',

  `link_rel` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT '',

  `link_notes` mediumtext COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL,

  `link_rss` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT ''

) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci;


-- --------------------------------------------------------


--

-- Table structure for table `wp_options`

--


CREATE TABLE `wp_options` (

  `option_id` bigint(20) UNSIGNED NOT NULL,

  `autoload` varchar(20) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci NOT NULL DEFAULT 'yes'

) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci;

Just follow these steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>From the dashboard of your site, navigate to Plugins &#8211;&gt; Add New.</li>\n<li>Select the Upload option and hit &#8220;Choose File.&#8221;</li>\n<li>When the popup appears select the the-events-calendar-x.x.zip file from your desktop. (The &#8216;x.x&#8217; will change depending on the current version number).</li>\n<li>Follow the on-screen instructions and wait as the upload completes.</li>\n<li>When it&#8217;s finished, activate the plugin via the prompt. A message will show confirming activation was successful. A link to access the calendar directly on the frontend will be presented here as well.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! Just configure your settings as you see fit, and you&#8217;re on your way to creating events in style. Need help getting things started? Check out our <a href=\"http://m.tri.be/2l\" rel=\"nofollow\">new user primer</a> for help with settings and features.</p>\n</p>\n<h4>Are there any troubleshooting steps you&#8217;d suggest I try that might resolve my issue before I post a new thread?</h4>\n<p>\n<p>First, make sure that you&#8217;re running the latest version of The Events Calendar (4.0 as of this release). If you&#8217;re running Events Calendar PRO it needs to match the version number of The Events Calendar. And if you&#8217;ve got any other add-ons, make sure those are current / running the latest code as well.</p>\n<p>The most common issues we see are either plugin or theme conflicts. You can test if a plugin or theme is conflicting by manually deactivating other plugins until just The Events Calendar is running on your site. If the issue persists from there, revert to the default Twenty Fourteen theme. If the issue is resolved after deactivating a specific plugin or your theme, you&#8217;ll know that is the source of the conflict.</p>\n<p>Note that we aren&#8217;t going to say &#8220;tough luck&#8221; if you identify a plugin/theme conflict. While we can&#8217;t guarantee 100% integration with any plugin or theme out there, we will do our best (and reach out the plugin/theme author as needed) to figure out a solution that benefits everyone.</p>\n</p>\n<h4>I&#8217;m still stuck. Where do I go to file a bug or ask a question?</h4>\n<p>\n<p>Users of the free The Events Calendar should post their questions in the plugin&#8217;s <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/support/plugin/the-events-calendar/\" rel=\"nofollow\">WordPress.org forum</a>, which we hit about once a week (usually on Wednesdays). Please make sure to read <a href=\"http://m.tri.be/19oc\" rel=\"nofollow\">our sticky post</a> providing an overview of the support we provide free users BEFORE posting. If you find you&#8217;re not getting support in as timely a fashion as you wish, you might want to consider purchasing a PRO license.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re already a PRO user, you&#8217;re entitled access to our more actively-monitored <a href=\"http://m.tri.be/2r\" rel=\"nofollow\">Events Calendar PRO forum</a> on our website. We can provide a deeper level of support here and hit these forums on a daily basis during the work week. Generally, except in times of increased support loads, we reply to all comments within 24-48 hours during the business week.</p>\n</p>\n<h4>Events Calendar PRO looks awesome! I&#8217;m sold! How can I get my hands on it?</h4>\n<p>\n<p>Events Calendar PRO can be purchased directly on <a href=\"http://m.tri.be/18wi\" rel=\"nofollow\">our website</a>. There are five (5) license types available, and all licenses include access to premium support, new feature releases, and regular maintenance updates.</p>\n</p>\n<h4>I&#8217;m interested in PRO or another add-on, but there are a few questions I&#8217;ve got before making the purchase. \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"The White Screen of Death: Why It Happens, and How to Fix It in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:67:\"http://theme-fusion.com/how-to-fix-white-screen-of-death-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:76:\"http://theme-fusion.com/how-to-fix-white-screen-of-death-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 05 Oct 2017 19:32:49 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:21:\"white screen of death\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"wordpress errors\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"http://theme-fusion.com/?p=406059\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:622:\"<p>The &#8216;White Screen of Death&#8217; (WSoD) is a horrible error for a website owner to encounter – one of the worst, in fact – especially if you don’t have the knowledge to fix it. With only a blank screen staring back at you, there’s absolutely no indication of what&#8217;s happened, and no way of knowing what to do [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com/how-to-fix-white-screen-of-death-wordpress/\">The White Screen of Death: Why It Happens, and How to Fix It in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com\">Theme Fusion</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Tom Rankin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15958:\"<p>The <a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Common_WordPress_Errors#The_White_Screen_of_Death\" target=\"_blank\">&#8216;White Screen of Death&#8217;</a> (WSoD) is a horrible error for a website owner to encounter – one of the worst, in fact – especially if you don’t have the knowledge to fix it. With only a blank screen staring back at you, there’s absolutely no indication of what&#8217;s happened, and no way of knowing what to do next.</p>\n<p><span id=\"more-406059\"></span></p>\n<p>However, like the childhood monsters lurking under your bed, there&#8217;s nothing to fear about the WSoD once you confront the problem head-on. All it takes is a logical process to root out the cause and get your website back online.</p>\n<p>In this article, we&#8217;ll look at what causes the WSoD, before running through six steps you can take to banish it forever, making everything right with the world once again.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s get started!</p>\n<h2>What Causes the White Screen of Death?</h2>\n<p>In a nutshell, the WSoD is a completely blank screen that greets you when trying to access your website. While there are many potential causes, you&#8217;ll typically find the issue is down to one of the following three:</p>\n<div class=\"shortcode-list\">\n<ol>\n<li>Incompatibility between your theme and a plugin (or plugins), or between plugins.</li>\n<li>A poorly coded theme or plugin.</li>\n<li>A low memory limit set by your hosting company (mostly seen in shared hosting environments).</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<p>Based on these reasons, we can start to build a plan of attack for dealing with the WSoD – so, let&#8217;s get cracking!</p>\n<h2>6 Steps to Fix the White Screen of Death on Your WordPress Website</h2>\n<p>There are six steps you&#8217;ll potentially need to carry out to fix your WSoD. We say &#8220;potentially&#8221;, because it&#8217;s likely you won&#8217;t need to carry out every step to fix the problem, so you can breathe a little easier! Furthermore, there&#8217;s nothing stopping you from tackling these steps in any order you like if you suspect a certain cause – we&#8217;ve just presented them in a logical order based on the most likely of issues.</p>\n<p>Finally, in order to complete these steps, you&#8217;ll need a File Transfer Protocol (FTP) manager. Don&#8217;t worry, they&#8217;re <a href=\"https://www.siteground.com/tutorials/ftp/ftp_client.htm\" target=\"_blank\">simple to use</a>, and just as easy as finding files on your computer. Once you&#8217;re ready, you&#8217;ll need to open your FTP manager of choice – we prefer using the open-source <a href=\"https://filezilla-project.org/\" target=\"_blank\">FileZilla</a>, though there are plenty of others out there to choose from.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Modify Your Memory Limit</h3>\n<p>Your WordPress hosting provider will allocate a certain amount of memory to your installed plugins, or for files that execute scripts (such as JavaScript), to enable them to operate correctly. If this is set too low, it could potentially cause the WSoD.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s worth mentioning upfront that some hosts won&#8217;t let you alter your memory directly – in these cases you&#8217;ll have to drop them a line and ask them to do it for you.</p>\n<p>To change your memory settings, you&#8217;ll need to open up your FTP manager, and connect to your server using the correct credentials (usually found within your host&#8217;s admin panel). Once entered, click <em>Quickconnect</em>:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406181\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ftp-connect.png\" alt=\"Logging into your FTP manager.\" width=\"633\" height=\"103\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ftp-connect.png 1566w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ftp-connect-300x49.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ftp-connect-768x125.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ftp-connect-1024x166.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 633px) 100vw, 633px\" /></figure>\n<p>You&#8217;ll see your website&#8217;s folders and files on the right hand side, so navigate to your &#8216;home&#8217; folder – likely called <em>public_html</em> or <em>www. </em>Once there look for a file called <em>wp-config.php</em>. Right-click it and select <em>View/Edit. </em>You may see a prompt asking you to choose a text editor, so select the default for now:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406182\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/config-view-edit.png\" alt=\"The config menu with View/Edit highlighted.\" width=\"452\" height=\"204\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/config-view-edit.png 904w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/config-view-edit-300x135.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/config-view-edit-768x347.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 452px) 100vw, 452px\" /></figure>\n<p>Once the file is open, type the following code on the next line after <em>&lt;?php</em>:</p>\n<p><em>define(‘WP_MEMORY_LIMIT’, ‘64M’);</em></p>\n<p>This tells your WordPress server to allocate a little more memory to your plugins. Having saved and closed the file, browse to your website. If you&#8217;re still experiencing the WSoD, you&#8217;ll need to move onto the next step.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Check for Incompatible Plugins</h3>\n<p>Plugins are an inherent part of WordPress, but they can also be the cause of website errors, including the WSoD. Fortunately, problematic plugins are quite simple to troubleshoot. Start by navigating to the <em>wp-content</em> folder within your FTP client:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406183\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/wp-content-folder.png\" alt=\"The wp-content folder.\" width=\"390\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/wp-content-folder.png 790w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/wp-content-folder-300x93.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/wp-content-folder-768x237.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 390px) 100vw, 390px\" /></figure>\n<p>Once inside, right-click on the <em>plugins</em> folder, select <em>Rename, </em>and append <em>-deactivated</em> to the folder name before pressing the <em>Return </em>key:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406184\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/plugins-rename.png\" alt=\"Renaming the plugin folder using the right-click menu.\" width=\"410\" height=\"285\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/plugins-rename.png 820w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/plugins-rename-300x209.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/plugins-rename-768x534.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 410px) 100vw, 410px\" /></figure>\n<p>The idea behind this is to stop WordPress from loading your plugins while you check for errors. Open your website again, and if it&#8217;s back online, a plugin <em>was</em> the cause of the WSoD.</p>\n<p>From here, rename your <em>plugins-deactivated</em> folder back to <em>plugins –</em> which will reactivate everything – then follow the above renaming process for each individual plugin within your <em>plugins</em> folder, one by one, until you find the one that causes the WSoD.</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve identified the faulty plugin, you&#8217;ll need to decide if the plugin is vital to your workflow. If it is, re-download the latest version, try reaching out to the developer for advice, or replace it with an alternative. Of course, if the plugin <em>isn&#8217;t</em> vital, trash it.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s worth mentioning that there could be more than one plugin causing the WSoD, in which case, you&#8217;ll have to identify both via the above approach.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Check for Incompatible Themes</h3>\n<p>If your WSoD woes are not memory or plugin related, the next step is to rule out your themes. Fortunately, this follows the same process as plugins – namely navigating to <em>wp-content</em>, and renaming your current theme&#8217;s folder to force WordPress to load the default <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/themes/twentysixteen/\" target=\"_blank\">Twenty Sixteen</a> theme:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406186\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/themes-rename-1.png\" alt=\"Renaming a theme using the right-click menu.\" width=\"394\" height=\"388\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/themes-rename-1.png 788w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/themes-rename-1-300x295.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/themes-rename-1-768x756.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/themes-rename-1-44x44.png 44w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 394px) 100vw, 394px\" /></figure>\n<p>If you you have deleted Twenty Sixteen, you&#8217;ll need to <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Using_Themes#Adding_New_Themes_Manually_.28FTP.29\" target=\"_blank\">upload it again manually</a> into your themes folder. Once done, check your site again. If it&#8217;s back online, a compatibility error between your theme and WordPress is the likely cause. At this point, you can attempt to contact the developer for advice, or choose an alternative theme – we suggest one with quality support and regular updates, <a href=\"http://avada.theme-fusion.com/\" target=\"_blank\">such as Avada</a>.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re still staring at a blank screen, it&#8217;s onto the next step.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Check for Blank Space Within Your Files</h3>\n<p>If you&#8217;ve been editing certain files such as <em>functions.php</em> and <em>wp-config.php, </em>blank lines within them can also cause the WSoD. For <em>wp-config.php</em>, this is relatively easy to fix. Using your FTP manager, navigate to the file and check for blank lines at the very start (before the opening <em>&lt;?php</em> tag), and at the very end. Simply deleting them, then saving the file, should be enough.</p>\n<p>The <em>functions.php </em>file is found within the <em>wp-includes</em> folder, and if you&#8217;ve been editing it, adding a rogue blank space is easily done. Unfortunately, due to its size, you may have trouble locating the offending line. The most practical solution is to replace your existing <em>functions.php</em> file with an unchanged version, then once again checking your website to see if the WSoD has disappeared.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Enable Error Reporting</h3>\n<p>WordPress&#8217; debug mode is like a powerful telescope, enabling you to hone in on exactly what&#8217;s wrong with your website. This step is handy, even if your WSoD problems are sorted, so let&#8217;s take a look.</p>\n<p>In your FTP manager, open up your <em>wp-config.php</em> file once more, and underneath the opening <em>&lt;?php</em> tag, add the following code:</p>\n<p><em>define(‘WP_DEBUG’, true);</em></p>\n<p><em>define(‘WP_DEBUG_LOG’, true);</em></p>\n<p><em>define(‘WP_DEBUG_DISPLAY’, false);</em></p>\n<p>Simply put, the first line activates the debug mode, the second tells WordPress to save a <em>debug.log</em> file in your home folder, and the third tells WordPress not to display these errors on your site for all and sundry to see.</p>\n<p>Each error within your <em>debug.log</em> file is pretty easy to interpret – the error shows the location within your WordPress directory along with a timestamp, and it&#8217;s likely going to be a theme or plugin that slipped through the net earlier in the investigation. To remedy it, follow the steps given previously, and the WSoD should be banished for good.</p>\n<h3>Step 6: Check Your File Permissions</h3>\n<p>Finally, while very rare, your WordPress install may have the wrong file permissions set somewhere along the line. You can view the permissions for a file or folder by right-clicking <em>File permissions…</em> within your FTP manager:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406187\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/file-permissions.png\" alt=\"Accessing file permissions from the right-click menu.\" width=\"384\" height=\"265\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/file-permissions.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/file-permissions-300x207.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 384px) 100vw, 384px\" /></figure>\n<p>Folders and files have different permissions represented by a number. Folders should look like this…</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406189\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/755-permission-example.png\" alt=\"An example of file permissions reading 755.\" width=\"304\" height=\"452\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/755-permission-example.png 608w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/755-permission-example-202x300.png 202w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 304px) 100vw, 304px\" /></figure>\n<p>…while files should look like this:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-406188\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/644-permission-example.png\" alt=\"An example of file permissions reading 644.\" width=\"272\" height=\"370\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/644-permission-example.png 544w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/644-permission-example-221x300.png 221w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 272px) 100vw, 272px\" /></figure>\n<p>Going deep on file permissions is outside the scope of this article – for an in-depth read, check out <a href=\"https://premium.wpmudev.org/blog/understanding-file-permissions/\" target=\"_blank\">this post</a> if you wish to understand them further.</p>\n<p>Because it&#8217;s a rare cause of the WSoD – not to mention the unenviable job of checking each individual file – if you&#8217;re not comfortable with this step, you may want to skip to our final section.</p>\n<h2>What to Do if You Can’t Fix the White Screen of Death</h2>\n<p>If you&#8217;re still experiencing the WSoD after carrying out all of these steps, other than <a href=\"http://www.refreshyourcache.com/en/home/\" target=\"_blank\">clearing your browser&#8217;s cache</a>, you may need to bite the bullet and contact your hosting provider for support.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re using a <a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/hosting/\" target=\"_blank\">trusted hosting provider</a>, you&#8217;ll find the resolution quick and painless – and more importantly, you&#8217;ll finally have your website back online.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>99% of the time, your WordPress website will work flawlessly. However, it&#8217;s the 1% that&#8217;ll potentially leave you tearing your hair out – especially when dealing with the <a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Common_WordPress_Errors#The_White_Screen_of_Death\" target=\"_blank\">White Screen of Death</a>, which doesn&#8217;t offer up many clues as to how to rectify it.</p>\n<p>You may not have known how to fix it previously, but with our guide, you’ll be back on track in no time. Let&#8217;s recap the steps you need to take:</p>\n<div class=\"shortcode-list\">\n<ol>\n<li>Modify your memory limit.</li>\n<li>Check for incompatible plugins and themes.</li>\n<li>Enable debug mode to glean any information about the error.</li>\n<li>Check for blank spaces within your WordPress files.</li>\n<li>Check your file permissions.</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<p>Do you have any further methods for fixing the White Screen of Death? Let’s hear them in the comments section below!</p>\n<p><em>Image credit: <a href=\"https://pixabay.com/en/drawing-pad-note-pad-1209781/\" target=\"_blank\">1681551</a>.</em></p>\n<p>The post <a \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:58:\"The 6 Reasons You Should Choose WordPress for Your Website\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"http://theme-fusion.com/reasons-to-choose-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"http://theme-fusion.com/reasons-to-choose-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 29 May 2017 00:37:42 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"Beginners Guide\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"New Site\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"choosing wordpress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"http://theme-fusion.com/?p=402943\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:656:\"<p>There are a number of solutions available for creating websites, each with their own advantages, disadvantages and fanatical user bases championing each of them. This means finding the solution to publish your content could be tough. Make the wrong choice and you&#8217;re potentially stuck with a platform that causes you headaches and grief further down the line. Fortunately, there&#8217;s [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com/reasons-to-choose-wordpress/\">The 6 Reasons You Should Choose WordPress for Your Website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com\">Theme Fusion</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Tom Rankin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18039:\"<p>There are a number of solutions available for creating websites, each with their own advantages, disadvantages and fanatical user bases championing each of them. This means finding the solution to publish your content could be tough. Make the wrong choice and you&#8217;re potentially stuck with a platform that causes you headaches and grief further down the line.</p>\n<p><span id=\"more-402943\"></span></p>\n<p>Fortunately, there&#8217;s a publishing platform available with the right balance of functionality, flexibility, cost, <em>and</em> support to match hand-coded websites and it also outperforms the other available solutions. That platform, of course, is WordPress!</p>\n<p>In this post, we will look at six reasons why WordPress should be the go-to publishing choice for your website, but first of all, let&#8217;s look at exactly what WordPress is, along with a little back history.</p>\n<h2>What Is WordPress?</h2>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-403465\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/wordpress-logo-1.png\" alt=\"WordPress logo\" width=\"1080\" height=\"246\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/wordpress-logo-1.png 1080w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/wordpress-logo-1-300x68.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/wordpress-logo-1-768x175.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/wordpress-logo-1-1024x233.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px\" /></figure>\n<p>Put simply, WordPress is a platform for publishing self-hosted websites. Its interface is accessed through your web browser and other than using a File Transfer Protocol (FTP) client for the initial install, WordPress offers you everything you need to publish your content. In fact, if you <a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/hosting/\" target=\"_blank\">choose the right host</a>, you wouldn&#8217;t even need an FTP client.</p>\n<p>WordPress was first launched in 2003 by two developers who wanted a better solution for publishing their blog content (<a href=\"http://ma.tt/\" target=\"_blank\">Matt Mullenweg</a> and <a href=\"https://mikelittle.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Mike Little</a>). 13 years later, WordPress has now grown to power over <a href=\"http://w3techs.com/technologies/history_overview/content_management/all/y\" target=\"_blank\">25% of the internet</a> – with high-profile users such as <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/\" target=\"_blank\">TechCrunch</a>, the <em><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Washington Post</a></em>, and <a href=\"http://www.bbcamerica.com/\" target=\"_blank\">BBC America</a>, to name a few.</p>\n<p>Its humble beginnings solely as a blogging platform are still present, but constant development has meant WordPress has evolved into a full-featured Content Management System (CMS). With developments such as the incoming <a href=\"http://v2.wp-api.org/\" target=\"_blank\">REST API</a> on the horizon, WordPress looks to become even more dominant in the future.</p>\n<p>Now we&#8217;ve briefly looked at its history, let&#8217;s take a deeper look at some of the reasons you should choose WordPress as your publishing platform.</p>\n<h2>1. WordPress Is Open-Source and Free Forever</h2>\n<p>You may have heard the term &#8216;open-source software&#8217; bandied around, but might not know what it means. Quite simply, open-source means anybody can contribute to the software in question, with all of the source code freely available to download and modify. In a lot of cases, open-source software is free to use. You may already be using open-source software without realizing it, such as the <a href=\"http://www.videolan.org/vlc/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">VLC media player</a>, or the <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.org/firefox\" target=\"_blank\">Firefox browser</a>:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-403033\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/mozilla-firefox-homepage.png\" alt=\"The Mozilla Firefox homepage.\" width=\"633\" height=\"387\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/mozilla-firefox-homepage.png 1942w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/mozilla-firefox-homepage-300x184.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/mozilla-firefox-homepage-768x470.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/mozilla-firefox-homepage-1024x626.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 633px) 100vw, 633px\" /></figure>\n<p>An important aspect of WordPress&#8217; freedom is its protection under what&#8217;s known as the <a href=\"http://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.en.html\" target=\"_blank\">GNU General Public Licence (GPL)</a>. This licence lets anybody use, share and modify the software. Also, in contrast to a standard copyright, any derived works must also be released under the GPL. What this means is WordPress is free, and will be freely available forever.</p>\n<p>While WordPress is highly unlikely to be unsupported in the future (WordPress&#8217; parent company Automattic was <a href=\"http://time.com/88025/wordpress-parent-automattic-joins-the-billion-dollar-club/\" target=\"_blank\">recently valued at $1–2 Billion</a>, and the CMS is the cornerstone of their business), its open-source nature means other developers are free to take over the project if development is halted. Plus, because of the GPL, they too would have to make their work freely available.</p>\n<h2>2. You Don&#8217;t Have to Be a Web Developer</h2>\n<p>There are a multitude of ways in which WordPress&#8217; design makes it easy to create pages and content, all without requiring any coding experience. In WordPress, each page or post is created using the open-source <a href=\"https://www.tinymce.com/\" target=\"_blank\">TinyMCE editor</a>. This gives WordPress the functionality of software like Microsoft Word or Google Docs, meaning styling your text with bold or italics, for example, can be done directly within the editor:</p>\n<figure><a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/tinymce-editor.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-403034\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/tinymce-editor.png\" alt=\"An example of the TinyMCE editor.\" width=\"633\" height=\"226\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/tinymce-editor.png 2348w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/tinymce-editor-300x107.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/tinymce-editor-768x274.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/tinymce-editor-1024x365.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 633px) 100vw, 633px\" /></a>Media can be embedded in a couple of ways. The Media Library enables you to add images using the <em>Add Media</em> button and can be resized directly within WordPress, so there&#8217;s no need for external programs such as Photoshop. &#8216;Under the hood&#8217; functionality also enables you to embed video from the likes of YouTube and Vimeo:</p>\n<p><img class=\"size-full wp-image-403035 aligncenter\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/video-embed-gif.gif\" alt=\"A GIF showing the video embed process in the TinyMCE editor.\" width=\"640\" height=\"365\" /></p>\n<p>There are many more examples of WordPress&#8217; ease of use, such as the infamous <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">five-minute install</a> procedure, <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Configuring_Automatic_Background_Updates\" target=\"_blank\">automatic updates</a> and its myriad of <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Settings_General_Screen\" target=\"_blank\">social sharing and user interaction</a> settings, among others, the content editing options are just the tip of the iceberg.</p>\n<h2>3. Designing Your Site Requires No Coding Skills</h2>\n<p>Your website&#8217;s overall design and layout doesn&#8217;t require the knowledge of your garden variety web developer either. For a start, WordPress includes several default themes designed to show off its core functionality. While these themes perform admirably, there are thousands of other themes to choose from, all completely free, within the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/themes/\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress Theme Directory</a>. </p>\n<p>Because they&#8217;re free, you&#8217;ll find that the quality of themes varies. However, the Theme Directory includes a five-star rating system, awarded by users, to help you make an informed choice.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-403037\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-theme-directory.png\" alt=\"The WordPress.org Theme Directory\" width=\"633\" height=\"370\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-theme-directory.png 1956w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-theme-directory-300x175.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-theme-directory-768x449.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-theme-directory-1024x599.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 633px) 100vw, 633px\" /></p>\n<p>There are also some developers who offer premium themes (i.e. ones with a cost attached) with a generally more committed development program and dedicated support. <a href=\"http://themeforest.net/\" target=\"_blank\">ThemeForest</a> is by far the largest site for purchasing premium themes and markets our very own <a href=\"https://themeforest.net/item/avada-responsive-multipurpose-theme/2833226?ref=ThemeFusion\" target=\"_blank\">Avada</a> – which is currently the number one selling theme:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://themeforest.net/item/avada-responsive-multipurpose-theme/2833226?ref=ThemeFusion\"><img src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/avada_wordpress_theme.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"360\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-427799\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/avada_wordpress_theme.jpg 700w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/avada_wordpress_theme-300x154.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\" /></a></figure>\n<h2>4. If You Need Extra Functionality, There&#8217;s a Plugin For That</h2>\n<p>The basic functionality of WordPress is very good and may be just what you&#8217;re looking for, but it doesn&#8217;t cover every need and want out of the box. You may need additional functionality and in WordPress this is provided by small add-ons called plugins:</p>\n<figure><a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/wordpress_plugins.jpg\"><img src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/wordpress_plugins.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1100\" height=\"710\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-427801\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/wordpress_plugins.jpg 1100w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/wordpress_plugins-300x194.jpg 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/wordpress_plugins-768x496.jpg 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/wordpress_plugins-1024x661.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\" /></a></figure>\n<p>There are thousands of plugins available for free within the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress Plugin Repository</a>, each providing different additional functionality. In some cases, such as <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\" target=\"_blank\">Super Cache</a> and <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wordpress-seo/\" target=\"_blank\">Yoast SEO</a>, free plugins found here can be practically essential.</p>\n<p>Similarly to themes, the premium plugin market is rich, with sites such as <a href=\"http://codecanyon.net/\" target=\"_blank\">CodeCanyon</a> offering thousands of plugins for purchase. Again, like premium themes, you&#8217;ll often find more committed development and dedicated support when compared to free options.</p>\n<h2>5. WordPress Has a Large, Strong Community</h2>\n<p>A major benefit of using WordPress is its strong, passionate, and inclusive community. The WordPress.org website has <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/support/\" target=\"_blank\">its own forums</a>, where users share advice and ask for help on a regular basis. If you have a question to ask, this is the place to do it! Many plugin and theme developers have support forums here for their free offerings too, so support is always at hand and you&#8217;ll more often than not, be talking directly to the developers themselves:</p>\n<figure><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-403041\" src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-forums.png\" alt=\"The WordPress.org forums.\" width=\"633\" height=\"326\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-forums.png 1942w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-forums-300x154.png 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-forums-768x395.png 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/wordpress-forums-1024x527.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 633px) 100vw, 633px\" /></figure>\n<p>Finally, as WordPress has grown, so has its developer base. The platform attracts contributors from all manner of other fields and industries, who pool their talents to make WordPress better. Updates to WordPress itself are frequent, with a team of hundreds releasing <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/news/category/releases/\" target=\"_blank\">three core updates per year</a>.</p>\n<h2>6. E-Commerce Is Easy With WordPress</h2>\n<p>Unlike a hand-coded website, setting up an e-commerce solution on your WordPress website is easy when using one of a number of available plugins.</p>\n<p>One such example is <a href=\"https://www.woothemes.com/woocommerce/\" target=\"_blank\">WooCommerce</a> – currently the most popular e-commerce solution available and integrated with Avada. Its strengths lie in how fast it is to set up a store and its support from all major payment providers.</p>\n<figure><a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/woocommerce-homepage.jpg\"><img src=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/woocommerce-homepage.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1200\" height=\"773\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-427803\" srcset=\"https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/woocommerce-homepage.jpg 1200w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/woocommerce-homepage-300x193.jpg 300w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/woocommerce-homepage-768x495.jpg 768w, https://theme-fusion.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/woocommerce-homepage-1024x660.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /></a></figure>\n<p>You&#8217;re not restricted to just WooCommerce though. There are other solutions available, such as <a href=\"https://easydigitaldownloads.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Easy Digital Downloads</a> (specializing in digital only products), and <a href=\"https://apps.shopify.com/shopify-for-wordpress\" target=\"_blank\">Shopify</a> as an alternative to both.</p>\n<p>Finally, while it&#8217;s not a WordPress-specific solution, by adding an open-source SSL certificate from <a href=\"https://letsencrypt.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Let&#8217;s Encrypt</a>, you could potentially build an online store with WordPress, Avada, WooCommerce, and Let&#8217;s Encrypt for very little outlay.</p>\n<h2>Next Steps</h2>\n<p>At this point, you&#8217;re probably on-board with the idea of using WordPress as the platform for publishing your website. If you&#8217;re itching to get started, here&#8217;s what to do next:<br />\n<div class=\"shortcode-list\">\n<ol>\n<li>Find a <a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/hosting/\" target=\"_blank\">suitable web host</a> for your website that ideally offers one-click WordPress install.</li>\n<li>Look for a theme that can help you create an amazing websites with advanced options that require no coding, is constantly updated and provides 5 star customer support, such as <a href=\"https://themeforest.net/item/avada-responsive-multipurpose-theme/2833226?ref=ThemeFusion\" target=\"_blank\">Avada</a>.</li>\n<li>Browse the WordPress.org <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/\" target=\"_blank\">Plugin Directory</a> to see the scope of what plugins are available for download.</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>Choosing a publishing platform for your website can be tough and choosing the wrong one means wasting time and money later, when migrating to a more suitable solution. WordPress should be your first choice for publishing your website. In this post we looked at some of the reasons why. Let&#8217;s recap:</p>\n<div class=\"shortcode-list\">\n<ol>\n<li>WordPress will be free forever.</li>\n<li>Using WordPress is as easy as using your favorite word processor.</li>\n<li>There are many free themes and very feature rich premium themes such as <a href=\"https://themeforest.net/item/avada-responsive-multipurpose-theme/2833226?ref=ThemeFusion\" target=\"_blank\">Avada</a>.</li>\n<li>You don&#8217;t have to know code in order to design and manage your site.</li>\n<li>WordPress can be extended with plugins to provide extra functionality.</li>\n<li>A large, strong community means you&#8217;ll never be without answers if you&#8217;re struggling.</li>\n<li>Selling products is easy, with several e-commerce solutions available to get started instantly.</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<p>What are you looking for in a WordPress website and what might be holding you back? Let us know in the comments section below!</p>\n<p><em>Image credit: <a href=\"https://pixabay.com/en/pick-and-mix-children-s-sweets-candy-171342/\" target=\"_blank\">9355</a>, <a target=\"_blank\">WordPress.org</a>.</em></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com/reasons-to-choose-wordpress/\">The 6 Reasons You Should Choose WordPress for Your Fusion</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"http://theme-fusion.com/reasons-to-choose-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"8\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:45:\"\n Fixes Added in 5.1.5\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"http://theme-fusion.com/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:60:\"http://theme-fusion.com/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 22 May 2017 17:42:53 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Avada\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Security\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Support\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"http://theme-fusion.com/?p=427600\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:519:\"<p>In Avada 5.1.5, we fixed two security issues which were in Avada versions 5.1.4 and below. This can always be found in our Changelog and we recommend to keep your theme up to date. It&#8217;s best to use auto updates and to also keep an eye on the Fusion Patcher tool as we typically issue [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/\">Security Fixes Added in 5.1.5</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com\">Theme Fusion</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"ThemeFusion Staff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9083:\"<p>In Avada 5.1.5, we fixed two security issues which were in Avada versions 5.1.4 and below. This can always be found in our <a href=\"http://theme-fusion.com/avada-documentation/changelog.txt\" target=\"_blank\">Changelog</a> and we recommend to keep your theme up to date. It&#8217;s best to use <a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/avada-doc/install-update/how-to-update-theme/#autoupdate\" target=\"_blank\">auto updates</a> and to also keep an eye on the <a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/avada-doc/install-update/avada-patcher/\" target=\"_blank\">Fusion Patcher</a> tool as we typically issue updates for security issues in less than 24 hours. </p>\n<p><span id=\"more-427600\"></span></p>\n<p>Like WordPress, we understand that security is not an absolute, it’s a continuous process and should be managed as such. While we try to be proactive in preventing security problems, we do not assume they’ll never come up. Our job is to quickly take care of them and work to get customers notified about them. The major difference here is that we do not get our customer emails.</p>\n<p>First off, the two issues fixed are below, and <a href=\"https://theme-fusion.com/knowledgebase/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/\" target=\"_blank\">you can read more about them here</a> and how to update the full theme which we recommend, or manual fix for older versions</p>\n<div class=\"shortcode-list\">\n<li> FIXED: Security fix to prevent additional calls to permalink structure (XSS)</li>\n<li> FIXED: Security fix that adds AJAX request verification for Fusion Builder content importer</li>\n</div>\n<p>Our development team immediately took action to check and verify the issue at hand. Once accurately identified, our team fixed it with a patch in less than 24 hours, and the full Avada 5.1.5 update was sent out in 4 days. Confirmation of the patch release date can be found here under 5.1.4: goo.gl/NGU83S … and confirmation of the changelog release that lists out the security fixes can be found here: goo.gl/40T2gp</p>\n<p>This was a unique situation for us because it started with a person who reported this and showed us the post they would make live. While we appreciate being made know of security or bug issues, and fix them quickly, we had major concerns over how we were approached. </p>\n<p>A bounty reward was being pursued, the content of the post they were making live explained how to fully use the exploit itself, in addition questions asked to hide those portions of the content were asked and we answered, but were ignored. The person hid their identity, ignored our requests and even published the post early. Most shockingly is the creator of that site had a script running that automatically creates their email as an admin user for the sites it’s run on. You can view this in their comments. While the script appears to be changed, even having such a thing should give anyone caution. We had no clue who we were dealing with, but clearly this was wrong. Anyone using Avada should check their user area of WP Admin and verify you know of all users listed.</p>\n<p><strong>There are several important factors to note:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>1.</strong> We (ThemeFusion) do not have all customer emails. In fact, we have less than 1/5th. Envato keeps them and does not give them to the authors who sell items. While we petition to get them, it goes nowhere so sending out a public blog post before everyone was made aware (through Envato&#8217;s eBlast) would of also made potential hackers aware who would take advantage of it.</p>\n<p><strong>2.</strong> Due to the above, we have no way of contacting all of our customers at once. In addition, we had concerns over the post of the reporter which explains how to use the exploit, and not knowing when they were sending out the post, we had to rely on Envato to do so.</p>\n<p><strong>3.</strong> Each time we send in a theme update, it lists out the changelog in detail. Both security issues were listed and their fixes approved by the Envato review team and the new version posted on the marketplace.</p>\n<p><strong>4.</strong> We did a similar thing to what WP did back in February and elected to put off disclosing the vulnerability to make sure that our users who use automatic updates on their sites – were protected before going public.</p>\n<p>We allowed customers to see auto updates for both the theme and the patcher tool and get as many updated as possible. The patcher tool description and changelog were descriptive in making users aware that security issues were fixed. Nor is this information buried as we described above, in fact they use the standard WordPress method of letting you know updates or patches are available and ready to apply. The changelog link is directly on the updates page in WP admin, the themes page as well, and the patcher tool describes each one in it’s location in WP admin. In addition, all of this is online at our support center.</p>\n<p><strong>5.</strong> This all being very recent, and in agreement with Envato about the security related customer notification, we expected the actual communiqué to be sent out to each person that has purchased Avada, which it has been. However we implicitly asked Envato to allow us to review the content of the email before it was sent. We wanted to review the content of the eBlast so that we can ensure our customers are being given the correct information and to include additional helpful information about the update or users who were updating from much older versions. Lastly, we asked to know exactly when it was sent out so we could time ours as well. Unfortunately Envato did not get in touch with us in time.</p>\n<p><strong>6.</strong> The day Envato did send out the eBlast to every customer, we received it as any customer would and then also posted the information on our site: https://theme-fusion.com/knowledgebase/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/</p>\n<p>We did inform our users about the available update that included the security fix through the several ways that we could: changelog, automatic patcher tool, a user through our private Facebook group and of course the automatic theme update. None of this information is buried. Even before we released 5.1.5, the security patch fix was done in 24 hours or less through our live patcher tool. Like it is in WordPress, it can be easily seen, that a patch/update is available. Both were labeled starting with “Security fix”, containing the kind of security issue “(ex: XSS)”.</p>\n<p><strong>Why did we wait some time before a publicly available disclosure was done from our side?</strong><br />\n<em>To protect our customers.</em> </p>\n<p><strong>How can this course of action protect customers?</strong><br />\n<em>We do know from website traffic checks, that our user base does update to new versions very fast. So making the update available, and using the more private information channels listed above (auto patch notifications, auto theme updates), we made sure that the majority of our users was already protected before the general public (which of course includes potential hackers) was made aware of the security issue through public blog posts.</em></p>\n<p>This is not an uncommon approach, but also something WordPress has done, examples below:<br />\n<a href=\"https://threatpost.com/wordpress-silently-fixed-privilege-escalation-vulnerability-in-4-72-update/123533/\" target=\"_blank\">https://threatpost.com/wordpress-silently-fixed-privilege-escalation-vulnerability-in-4-72-update/123533/</a><br />\n<a href=\"http://www.securityweek.com/wordpress-delayed-disclosure-critical-vulnerability\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.securityweek.com/wordpress-delayed-disclosure-critical-vulnerability</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.imperva.com/blog/2017/03/early-vulnerability-disclosure-thwarts-wordpress-hackers/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.imperva.com/blog/2017/03/early-vulnerability-disclosure-thwarts-wordpress-hackers/</a></p>\n<p>The issue itself has been resolved over a month ago, a patch created in 24 hours or less once we were notified and our user base was informed about it (automatically) through our changelog, our live patcher tool and a post in our private Facebook group. That is as much as we can do since we do not have all customer emails. Lastly and finally, Envato sent the full eBlast to all customers last week. Time in-between users updating and a public disclosure is needed for a reason.</p>\n<p>Our customers know we are not negligent in any way, they know we do everything possible for them and this involves fixing any and all security or bug issues. We campaign tirelessly for all of our customers, to maintain their installs and ensure that the theme is always updated or a patch applied.</p>\n<p>We will keep doing what we always have done and build strong relationships with our customers through trust and communication.</p>\n<p>ThemeFusion</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/\">Security Fixes Added in 5.1.5</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://theme-fusion.com\">Theme Fusion</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"http://theme-fusion.com/security-fixes-added-5-1-5/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"10\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:29:\"http://theme-fusion.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"hourly\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";O:42:\"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary\":1:{s:7:\"\0*\0data\";a:17:{s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Mon, +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"language\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"en-US\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"item\";a:10:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"\n \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"Going Gutenberg: Chapter I\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-i/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 19 Jan 2018 21:05:18 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Articles\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"Going Gutenberg\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1423673\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:630:\"<p>We&#8217;ve made significant rewrites and refactors of our products over the years, but adapting our plugins to fully integrate with the new editor coming in WordPress version 5.0—code-named &#8220;Gutenberg&#8221;—is the biggest ecosystem change we’ve faced since the introduction of custom post types. Agencies and developers have been speaking out in large number and loud volume&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-i/\">Going Gutenberg: Chapter I</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"George\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11379:\"<p>We&#8217;ve made significant rewrites and refactors of our products over the years, but adapting our plugins to fully integrate with the new editor coming in WordPress version 5.0—code-named &#8220;Gutenberg&#8221;—<strong>is the biggest ecosystem change we’ve faced since the introduction of custom post types.</strong></p>\n<p>Agencies and developers have been speaking out in large number and loud volume about their hopes, fears, and predictions for how Gutenberg will change the WordPress world. This blog post isn&#8217;t about that—we&#8217;ll instead take a specific look at how The Events Calendar will be affected by Gutenberg, and how we plan to grow our plugins to take advantage of everything the new editor has to offer.</p>\n<h3>Why Gutenberg is Worth the Effort</h3>\n<p>Our existing metaboxes and shortcodes will continue to work for a long time in the new editor. This means that there are two main roads we can embark on:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>We could just make minimal changes to ensure nothing breaks. This is the cheapest option, and lets us focus on our existing roadmap of new plugin features.</li>\n<li>We could fully embrace Gutenberg, and look for new opportunities to improve our products as the foundations of WordPress itself change.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>We’ve chosen the second path. It’s the more expensive route, and requires us to shift our focus away from other things we’re excited to build. But for years, we at <a href=\"http://tri.be\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Modern Tribe</a> (makers of The Events Calendar) have been obsessed with the evolution of content creation, and how we can improve the experience of creating events. <strong>Just making things &#8220;not-break&#8221; is an inadequate response to such a unique opportunity</strong> to change the content-creation experience in WordPress on a foundational level.</p>\n<p>We are generally optimistic about Gutenberg, and think most of our users will love it and the opportunities it provides. The editing experience is <em>truly</em> better, along with these other benefits:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Better/More-Enjoyable Code</strong> — The new blocks system takes advantage of what modern JavaScript has to offer. As we’ll likely explore in a future <em>Going Gutenberg</em> post, creating blocks—even with advanced features—is simpler and more flexible than creating PHP metaboxes.</li>\n<li><strong>Reusable Blocks</strong> — If you find yourself entering the same data on events, or even just the same <em>kind</em> of data, you can save the block as a “Reusable Block”, and save the time and energy you’d spend recreating the block from scratch each subsequent time. There is nothing in the current editor like this.</li>\n<li><strong>Customizable Events Display</strong> — We’re often asked how to move this event detail above that event detail, or how to put event tickets information in a certain place on the single-event view, etc. Blocks would allow users to drag and drop event and ticket data pretty much anywhere they’d like, giving them a ton of freedom to design their event layouts without editing the theme.</li>\n<li><strong>Foundations for Future Change</strong> — Gutenberg is not <em>just</em> about the editor. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/gutenberg/handbook/reference/faq/#what-features-will-be-available-at-launch-what-does-the-post-launch-roadmap-look-like\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">In the words of the Gutenberg team</a>: “With the editor, we lay the foundation for bigger things when it comes to page building and customization. A lot of features are planned, too many to list. But a rough roadmap is: v1) post and page editor v2) page template editor, v3) site builder.” The slower we are to adapt to v1, the slower we’ll be to adapt to v2, and the less experience we’ll have with the new ways of doing things.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Why Gutenberg is a Little Scary</h3>\n<p>The new editor doesn’t <em>only</em> bring unanimously-great things—there are some issues we foresee when the editor goes live in April, and some issues we’re already running into.</p>\n<h4>Issues We’re Already Running Into</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>No Custom Block Categories (Yet)</strong> — Blocks are currently only allowed to fit into one of the following categories: “Common Blocks”, “Layout Blocks”, “Widgets”, and “Embeds”. We think it would be nice to create a custom category for event blocks to keep things a little more organized. The search feature in the add-blocks panel prevents this from being a huge pain for now, but custom categories is definitely something we’d love to see and hope <a href=\"https://github.com/WordPress/gutenberg/pull/1732#issuecomment-357793217\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">the current efforts to implement it</a> are a success.</li>\n<li><strong>What Becomes a Block? What Goes in the Settings Sidebar?</strong> — The solution to this question may <em>seem</em> obvious: Anything that’ll render on the front-end is a block, while anything that doesn’t (and relates more to event meta details, for example) goes in the settings sidebar. But with some event, venue, and ticket information, it’s not clear whether making it a block or putting it in the settings sidebar is the best choice.</li>\n<li><strong>High Technological Barrier to Entry</strong> — While we have some serious experts, our entire team isn’t 100% fluent in React. Many of us are working hard to learn and catch up, but for now there’s an unfair burden on the core developers who <em>do</em> know React very well. At the same time, it’s unrealistic to expect every team member to become a JavaScript master; gaining <em>deep</em> knowledge of React and other modern JavaScript technologies takes considerable time.</li>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Please Note:</strong> We are <a href=\"https://tri.be/careers/#openings\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">looking for two experienced front-end WordPress devs</a> to join the team! Get in touch if you’re interested or know someone who’s looking.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Issues We’re Anticipating</h4>\n<p>There are certain issues endemic to a change this size that have nothing to do with Gutenberg specifically. Scope creep is a real challenge, for example, as we try to figure out what features are “nice-to-haves” and what features are truly essential. Scheduling a change this large with a team as large as ours is another challenge in its own right, and we’ve also got some concerns about testing our changes to ensure we “play nice” with the other plugins and themes our hundreds of thousands of users rely on.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Customer Agita</strong> — As great as Gutenberg is, there will inevitably be some subset of users who absolutely hate it, especially if its release breaks things on their site. We’re working hard to ensure our excellent support team is educated and ready to handle the myriad questions sure to come.</li>\n<li><strong>Compatibility Across Add-ons</strong> — The Events Calendar is the most popular plugin we make, but add-ons like Events Calendar PRO and Filter Bar have <em>huge</em> audiences as well. We worry about issues arising if The Events Calendar is fully Gutenberg-ready while other plugins are not yet compatible. We’re prioritizing our most popular plugins (and any that touch the post editor) to minimize possible issues on this front.</li>\n<li><strong>Compatibility with Third-Party Plugins</strong> — We can’t only look inward when it comes to worrying about compatibility. We need to make sure that whatever changes we make won’t affect third-party plugins negatively, especially the plugins people most heavily rely on like WPML, Yoast SEO, Jetpack, and more. We also worry about <em>their</em> impact on <em>our</em> plugins.</li>\n<li><strong>Graceful Handling of Prior Site Customizations</strong> — While we don’t have hard numbers, we probably have five- to six-figure numbers of users who’ve customized their sites in some way via the Customizer, child themes, custom template files, our <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/extensions/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">official Extensions</a>, or some combination of these and other methods. Ensuring a smooth upgrade path for these users is challenging, but crucial.</li>\n<li><strong>Too Many Options</strong> — There’s something to be said about having all of the event details in one metabox. We think breaking this out into blocks is the right move, but do worry that some users will find it a little confusing or complicated to have a separate block for each &#8220;event details&#8221; component.</li>\n<li><strong>Building Events on Mobile Devices</strong> — We’re not really sure what the experience of using blocks will be like on mobile devices, especially touch-screen ones. While the current metabox system doesn’t make for an award-winning experience, it’s fairly easy to create events and fill out event details on an iPhone or Android device; we don’t want to lose that functionality.</li>\n<li><strong>Accessibility</strong> — We care very much about accessibility, as do the many universities and other institutions that use The Events Calendar. But we don’t know much about how accessible the blocks system will be. “Accessibility is not an afterthought,” The Gutenberg Handbook <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/gutenberg/handbook/reference/faq/#will-gutenberg-be-made-properly-accessible\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">currently states</a>, before admitting, “Not every aspect of Gutenberg is accessible at the moment.”</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>The Road Ahead</h3>\n<p>The point of this blog series, <em><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/tag/going-gutenberg/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Going Gutenberg</a></em>, is to document our journey as we go from having no support for the Gutenberg editor to having <strong>full</strong> compatibility with it. We will start with an <strong>optional</strong> Gutenberg-friendly event editor that we hope to release before WordPress 5.0 officially arrives.</p>\n<p>The next installment of this series will showcase some early design work for that editor. It’ll also reveal other changes we’re planning for the event post type, our widgets and shortcodes, and more. Be sure to <a href=\"https://confirmsubscription.com/h/r/F35BA2B75B521339\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">subscribe to this blog</a> and/or follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/theeventscalendar\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheEventsCal\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a> to stay abreast of our progress—and our roadblocks.</p>\n<hr style=\"width:30%;margin-left:35%;margin-right:35%;\">\n<p><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/2.3/72x72/1f514.png\" alt=\"🔔\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> <strong>Please Note:</strong> This is a blog series about active development and exploration. Anything we mention here is subject to change, and this blog series should be read as a tentative roadmap for our products—not an official release plan.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-i/\">Going Gutenberg: Chapter I</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events long support; hello Help Desk! When we first launched our plugins, we used bbPress to create a set of support forums that were open for everyone to research. In typical forum fashion, users could collaborate with each other and make use of existing answers to help answer their own questions. However, some users needed&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/introducing-help-desk/\">Introducing: Help Desk</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"Hillary Schlaht\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1985:\"<p>So long support; hello Help Desk!</p>\n<p>When we first launched our plugins, we used bbPress to create a set of support forums that were open for everyone to research. In typical forum fashion, users could collaborate with each other and make use of existing answers to help answer their own questions.</p>\n<p>However, some users needed to share things confidentially. To accommodate that we added the ability to post private replies. This was really useful, but it didn’t meet the needs of users who needed the <em>entire</em> conversation to be private.</p>\n<p>In response to customer feedback, we’ve gradually tweaked the support process to improve the support experience and go beyond what conventional forums have to offer. To reflect these changes, we’ve decided it’s time to rebrand our Support Forums. From now on, they will be known as the “Help Desk”.</p>\n<h2>Introducing, Help Desk!</h2>\n<p>Essentially, the Help Desk format enables you to create a private conversation and receive direct help from our community team for your specific issue &#8211; without anyone else viewing your posts or joining in on the conversation.</p>\n<p>If you like, you still have the option of submitting your query publicly so that other users can learn from the response you receive. These options enable us to offer the best of public forums alongside the privacy of traditional help desk solutions.</p>\n<p>You are also still welcome to comment on other’s queries if you have questions regarding a particular thread. If you do, we’ve put a system in place to help guide you to the most direct and helpful response.</p>\n<p>The new Help Desk format is the first of many changes we’re planning to make to support in 2018. Stay tuned for more awesome!</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/introducing-help-desk/\">Introducing: Help Desk</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"Team Trips: Why do we do it?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/team-trips-why-do-we-do-it/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 19 Jan 2018 13:57:57 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Lifestream\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1425197\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:592:\"<p>We’re about to embark on our annual team trip! This year’s destination: Placencia, Belize. Although we have a lot of fun on these trips, they are also an important part of our yearly goal-setting.
